{{2010 Summer Youth Olympics}}
This page is a '''chronological summary''' of the '''[[2010 Summer Youth Olympics]]''', the inaugural [[Youth Olympic Games]], held in [[Singapore]].
== Calendar == {{2010 Summer Youth Olympics calendar}}
== Pre-Games == '''2001''' * [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) president [[Jacques Rogge]] announced plans for an Olympic Games for youths aged 14 to 18.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/6467087.stm | work=BBC News | title=Rogge wants Youth Olympic Games | date=2007-03-19}}</ref>
'''July 2007''' * IOC members at the [[List of IOC meetings#IOC Sessions|119th IOC session]] in [[Guatemala City]], Guatemala ratified the proposal for the Youth Olympic Games, the first of which would be held in 2010.<ref name="ratified">{{Cite web |url=http://en.beijing2008.cn/news/official/ioc/n214106925.shtml# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204053148/http://en.beijing2008.cn/news/official/ioc/n214106925.shtml# |archive-date=2009-02-04 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> * Bidding for the 1st Summer Youth Olympics in 2010 was opened to the [[National Olympic Committees]] (NOCs).<ref name="ratified"/>
'''21 January 2008''' * A postal vote by the [[International Olympic Committee]] Executive Board io the week before saw [[Moscow]] and Singapore being shortlisted to host the Games, defeating the three other candidates, [[Athens]], [[Bangkok]] and [[Turin]].<ref>http://www.gamesbids.com/eng/index.php?news=1200917900</ref>
'''21 February 2008''' * Singapore won the [[Bids for the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics|bid]] to host the first Youth Olympic Games, winning finalist [[Moscow]] with a vote of 53 to 44 by [[International Olympic Committee]] members.<ref>http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/330241/1/.html</ref>
'''2 August 2008''' * The first Youth [[Olympic Village]] was moved from the [[National University of Singapore]]'s University Town to the campus of [[Nanyang Technological University]], with [[Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee|SYOGOC]] citing rising construction costs.<ref>http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/364499/1/.html</ref>
'''21 November 2009''' * The official [[mascots]] of the Games, [[Lyo and Merly]], were announced. They were introduced by [[Ministry of Community Development, Youth and Sports|Minister for Community Development, Youth and Sports]] [[Vivian Balakrishnan|Dr Vivian Balakrishnan]] at [[Suntec City]] in Singapore.<ref>https://archive.is/20120910000246/http://www.singapore2010.sg/public/sg2010/en/en_news/en_media_releases/en_20091121_mascot_debut.html</ref><ref>http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1019684/1/.html</ref>
'''30 May 2010''' * [[Everyone (Olympics song)|''Everyone'']], the official [[theme song]] of the Games, written by local producer [[Ken Lim]] and sung by five artistes from the five continents, premiered worldwide.<ref>https://archive.is/20120909133344/http://www.singapore2010.sg/public/sg2010/en/en_news/en_media_releases/en_20100527_everyone_an_anthem_for_youth_around_the_world.html</ref>
'''23 July 2010''' * The first ever Youth [[Olympic Flame]] was lit in [[Ancient Olympia]], Greece, beginning the round-the-world journey spanning the five continents up till 5 August.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamesbids.com/eng/youth_olympic_bids/other_youth_olympic_news/1216135274.html# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727211243/http://www.gamesbids.com/eng/youth_olympic_bids/other_youth_olympic_news/1216135274.html# |archive-date=2010-07-27 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
'''5 August 2010''' * The Youth Olympic Flame (JYOF) arrived in Singapore ahead of the Games to be held nine days later. The torch will travel for six days around the island country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamesbids.com/eng/youth_olympic_bids/other_youth_olympic_news/1216135293.html# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106063027/http://www.gamesbids.com/eng/youth_olympic_bids/other_youth_olympic_news/1216135293.html# |archive-date=2012-01-06 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
== Games == ;12 August 2010 * The [[Football at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics#Girls|girls' football preliminary round]] was the first sport to begin, commencing before the opening ceremony.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}
=== Day 1 (August 14) === ;Opening ceremony'' * The Olympic cauldron was lit by Singaporean sailor [[Darren Choy]],<ref>{{cite news | last = Ngoo | first = Irene | title = YOG opening ceremony, Part 1 | url = http://blogs.straitstimes.com/2010/8/14/yog-opening-ceremony | work = [[The Straits Times]] | date = 14 August 2010 | accessdate = 14 August 2010 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100817002257/http://blogs.straitstimes.com/2010/8/14/yog-opening-ceremony | archivedate = 17 August 2010 | df = }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Ngoo | first = Irene | title = YOG opening ceremony, Part 2 | url = http://blogs.straitstimes.com/2010/8/14/yog-opening-ceremony-part-2 | work = [[The Straits Times]] | date = 14 August 2010 | accessdate = 14 August 2010 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100817011009/http://blogs.straitstimes.com/2010/8/14/yog-opening-ceremony-part-2 | archivedate = 17 August 2010 | df = }}</ref> signalling the commencement of the inaugural Youth Olympic Games.
=== Day 2 (August 15) === ;[[Triathlon at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics|Triathlon]] * [[Yuka Sato (triathlete)|Yuka Sato]] of Japan won the first ever gold medal at the Youth Olympic Games, in the [[Triathlon at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics – Girls'|girls' triathlon]] event.<ref name="USA Today">{{cite news|last=Casey |first=Michael |title=Japan's Sato wins first gold in Youth Olympics |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2010-08-15-2752305217_x.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=15 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rzlFmSIO?url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2010-08-15-2752305217_x.htm |archivedate=15 August 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
=== Day 3 (August 16) === ;[[Taekwondo at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics|Taekwondo]] * Host nation [[Singapore at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics|Singapore]] received its first medal at the Youth Olympics when taekwondo exponent Daryl Tan entered the semi-finals, virtually guaranteeing him a bronze medal at the least.<ref>http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/Sport/Story/STIStory_567014.html</ref>
=== Day 4 (August 17) === ;[[Weightlifting at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics|Weightlifting]] * Chinese weightlifter Deng Wei won the [[Weightlifting at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics#Girls|women's 58-kilogram event]], setting a new junior world record in the process.<ref>https://archive.is/20120912010024/http://www.singapore2010.sg/public/sg2010/en/en_news/en_stories/en_20100817_golden_girl_deng_wei-_sets_junior_world_record.html</ref>
=== Day 5 (August 18) === {{Empty section|date=January 2011}}
=== Day 6 (August 19) === ;[[Archery at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics|Archery]] * Korean archer Kwak Ye Ji broke the outdoor junior women's world record with a score of 670 in the 70m (72 arrows) ranking round, breaking the previous record of 666 set compatriot Um Hye-Rang in 2001, and was three points away from the Olympic record set by Ukrainian [[Lina Herasymenko]].<ref>https://archive.is/20120912025239/http://www.singapore2010.sg/public/sg2010/en/en_news/en_stories/en_20100819_daily_wrap_junior_womens_archery_world_record_shattered_in_singapore.html</ref>
