{{Technical|date=May 2015}}
The '''phonological word''' or '''prosodic word''' (also called '''pword''', '''PrWd'''; symbolised as ω) is a [[Constituent (linguistics)|constituent]] in the [[phonological hierarchy]] higher than the [[syllable]] and the [[Foot (prosody)|foot]] but lower than [[Prosodic unit|intonational phrase]] and the [[phonological phrase]]. It is largely held (Hall, 1999) to be a [[prosodic domain]] in which phonological [[distinctive feature|features]] within the same [[lexeme]] may spread from one [[Morph (linguistics)|morph]] to another or from one [[clitic]] to a [[clitic host]] or from one clitic host to a clitic.

==References==
*Hall, T. A. (1999). "The phonological word: a review" In: T. A. Hall & Ursula Kleinhenz (eds.) ''Studies on the Phonological Word''. 1-22. Amsterdam: John Benjamins.

